Can the euro be fixed?
Paris - German Finance Minister Schäuble recently put the option of Greece exiting the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state is exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a major discussion about the principles underlying the euro, the euro governance model, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before the publication of the Schaubler plan, European leaders had already noticed a report on the future of the euro written by Jean-Claude Juncker, President of the European Commission, and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, new debates about Greece led many decision-makers to believe that it was necessary to return to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens were questioning why they should share a single currency.
Does this make sense? Can a consensus be formed about Greece's future?
Money is like a nation; it requires a myth to establish it.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was the political price Germany paid to France for reunification.
In fact, Germany's reunification was merely the final step of an engineering project that had already taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing dilemma.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, believing they were incompatible with the single market; at the same time, they were unwilling to maintain for long the monetary system dominated by the German central bank.
A genuine European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
Looking back, Germany's reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was in severe difficulties; France was undervalued and its economy was booming.
Over the following decade, the imbalance gradually emerged between Germany, which was re-emerging, and other countries experiencing a credit boom due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the 2008 global financial crisis, these conditions became the breeding ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would have become without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate regime continue or collapse?
Will the German mark be overvalued again?
Will countries reimpose trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will government reform be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analysis baseline to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is certainly not a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the economic performance of the eurozone has been consistently disappointing, and its political system must be held accountable for this.
What is truly important is whether the common European currency will still be significant in the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginably high (and if the eurozone disintegrates during a crisis, exacerbating mutual conflicts among member states, the costs would increase even further).
Moreover, abolishing the euro may unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke of the University of Oxford recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple remains married because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still have meaning?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assume that the monetary union can promote economic integration and consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
In contrast, internal trade and investment growth within the eurozone have been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not gone further than unifying currency to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the power they still have.
This may make sense politically, but it is economically nonsensical: Europe's vast internal market is one of its main assets, so there can be no waste of an opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hope that the euro becomes one of the major international currencies (particularly considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy frameworks).
However, according to the latest European Central Bank data, this hope has been largely realized.
The international use of the euro ranks second only to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an insignificant entity.
Third, people (naively) believe that the institutions underpinning the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the level of policy-making in Europe as a whole were inherently higher than that at the national level.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test emerged: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, leading to a worse performance compared to the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further reforms of policy systems are necessary.
But the formulation and implementation of a schedule require a wide consensus on the nature of the problem.
The ongoing debates over the Greek issue demonstrate that Europe is still far from reaching a consensus: the participating countries offer contradictory analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, and consequently, they prescribe contradictory solutions.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was significantly hindered by the differing patterns of transmission across countries.
All countries favor joint actions, but they cannot reach a unified plan because they disagree on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this issue is not insurmountable, as evidenced by major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the initiation of a banking union.
Discrepancies did not prevent the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, demonstrating that institutional governance is indeed crucial.
But the reforms and actions only began recently, and were implemented under severe crisis pressures, a fact that has made the difficulties of reaching consensus clear to everyone.
Europe can no longer delay and pretend.
Eurozone member states must form a consistent agenda on governance and political reform to transform the monetary union into an engine of prosperity. Otherwise, they will be doomed to sink into recurring disputes and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and major reforms.
Now, all major stakeholders are obligated to clearly define what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to trade in exchange for what they want.
